## Suggested joke flow

Provide:

* A randomly selected unused joke
* A **“Give me another”** button
* A button to select the current suggestion
* A clear display of setup and punchline
* Avoid immediately repeating the same suggestion
* Prefer jokes absent from the archive
* Fall back to the full suggestions list if all suggestions have been used

## Custom joke flow

Allow either:

* One-line joke
* Setup and punchline

Use a simple selector or tabs.

Validate that required fields are not empty.

Apply sensible maximum lengths, for example:

* One-line joke: 500 characters
* Setup: 300 characters
* Punchline: 300 characters

Display character counts.

Do not allow arbitrary HTML.

## Submission

When the user clicks **“This is my joke for the day”**, construct a GitHub issue creation URL.

Use either:

* A GitHub Issue Form with query parameters where supported
* Or a normal pre-filled issue body URL

Prefer an Issue Form if it produces a reliable structured issue body.

The issue should include:

* Submission date
* Joke type
* Setup, punchline, or text
* A hidden machine-readable marker
* A version marker for the submission format

Example body:

```markdown
## Daily joke submission

**Date:** 2026-07-27
**Format version:** 1
**Joke type:** setup-punchline

<!-- daily-joke-submission:start -->
<!-- date:2026-07-27 -->
<!-- type:setup-punchline -->

### Setup

Why did the developer go broke?

### Punchline

Because they used up all their cache.

<!-- daily-joke-submission:end -->
```

Use clear delimiters so the Action script can parse the body safely.

The issue title should be:

```text
Daily joke: 2026-07-27
```

The issue must receive a `daily-joke` label.

Document that this label must exist, or create it automatically using the GitHub CLI in the workflow if practical.

The frontend should explain that GitHub will open in a new page and the user must submit the issue to complete the process.

Do not claim that the joke is recorded merely because the issue creation page was opened.

## Schedule

Display all configured schedule entries.

Show:

* Date
* Assigned person
* Status

Suggested statuses:

* Recorded
* Missed
* Today
* Upcoming

Determine “missed” when:

* The date is earlier than today
* There is a schedule entry
* No archive entry exists

Use playful status text, but retain clear icons or labels.

Example:

```text
27 July — Alice — Recorded
28 July — Bob — Recorded
29 July — Charlie — Failed the department
30 July — Si — Today
31 July — Alice — Upcoming
```

## Archive

Display archived jokes in date order.

Show:

* Date
* Team member
* Joke
* Link to the original GitHub issue

The issue link can be constructed from the configured repository owner, repository name, and stored issue number.

Add a print-friendly mode so the archive can be printed or saved as PDF when the original team joker returns.

Add a heading such as:

```text
The Collected Works of the Temporary Jesters
```

Include a print stylesheet that hides navigation, buttons, controls, and other irrelevant UI.

